":"NYC judge continuing Ingersoll legal tradition","body":"Charles Dennis Ingersoll continued the Ingersoll family legal tradition across the New York and Connecticut bars — making him the fourth consecutive generation of Ingersoll lawyers and judges descending from Rev. Jonathan Ingersoll. His grandfather Jonathan Ingersoll Jr. was Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut; his father Charles Anthony Ingersoll was a US federal judge; his uncle Ralph Isaacs Ingersoll was a US Congressman and Minister to Russia; his cousin Charles Roberts Ingersoll became Governor of Connecticut. The Ingersoll legal dynasty spanned 1747-1905 (Rev. Jonathan to Charles Dennis) across five generations."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Married widow Katharine Sanders Varnum, 1885","body":"Charles Dennis married Katharine Corse Sanders Varnum on June 2, 1885 in Manhattan New York — she had previously been married to Robert Taylor Varnum. The couple had three children together: Hamilton Ingersoll (1888-1940), Anita Ingersoll Gwynne (1891-1970), and Justine Ingersoll Arnold (1893-1984). His grandchildren through these three children form the documented twentieth-century Ingersoll-Arnold-Gwynne descendants of the original Connecticut bar family."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"New Haven 1843 to Manhattan 1905, Green-Wood Cemetery","body":"Charles Dennis Ingersoll was born January 15, 1843 in New Haven Connecticut and died January 8, 1905 in Manhattan New York at age sixty-one. He is buried at Green-Wood Cemetery in Greenwood Heights Brooklyn New York — breaking the Ingersoll family Grove Street Cemetery tradition through his NYC career. His wife Katharine died in Menton France in 1922."}],"quotes":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"military_service":[],"education":[],"career":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Judge Charles Dennis Ingersoll","first_name":"Charles","last_name":"Ingersoll","middle_name":"Dennis","married_names":[],"